their own credit--

00:04:19.227 --> 00:04:20.560
essentially, their own currency.

00:04:20.560 --> 00:04:22.690
Every person would have
their own currency.

00:04:22.690 --> 00:04:26.620
Super interesting concept
that was a big part of what

00:04:26.620 --> 00:04:28.330
influenced us.

00:04:28.330 --> 00:04:31.720
Fast forward to 2011, and
there was these three geniuses

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:33.130
that got together--

00:04:33.130 --> 00:04:37.032
Arthur Britto, Jed McCaleb,
and David Schwartz.

00:04:37.032 --> 00:04:38.740
And this is, of course,
after Bitcoin was

00:04:38.740 --> 00:04:40.031
created a couple years earlier.

00:04:40.031 --> 00:04:42.350
They were fascinated
by what Bitcoin did,

00:04:42.350 --> 00:04:45.520
but they were frustrated by
the enormous waste of energy

00:04:45.520 --> 00:04:47.350
that is at the heart of mining.

00:04:47.350 --> 00:04:49.990
That's the core part of Bitcoin.

00:04:49.990 --> 00:04:53.350
So they set out to build a more
efficient consensus algorithm,

00:04:53.350 --> 00:04:55.990
and they came up with
something really beautiful.

00:04:55.990 --> 00:04:58.090
They also were inspired
by what Ryan Fugger had

00:04:58.090 --> 00:05:00.880
done at The Ripple
Project, and also

00:05:00.880 --> 00:05:04.270
brought in that idea of
pathfinding algorithm

00:05:04.270 --> 00:05:07.630
so that anything of value
can be exchanged along

00:05:07.630 --> 00:05:09.740
with that digital
asset to really--

00:05:09.740 --> 00:05:13.054
I think that was the birth
point of this internet of value.

00:05:13.054 --> 00:05:14.720
