When you think of any
distributed system, when

00:11:26.969 --> 00:11:28.510
you take a distributed
systems class,

00:11:28.510 --> 00:11:29.440
the first thing
your professor will

00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:30.981
tell you is your
distributed system's

00:11:30.981 --> 00:11:33.370
still only going to be as
good as the nodes it runs on.

00:11:33.370 --> 00:11:34.953
And so if you think
of bitcoin miners,

00:11:34.953 --> 00:11:37.570
they're only incentivized to
basically hash as efficiently

00:11:37.570 --> 00:11:38.230
as possible.

00:11:38.230 --> 00:11:40.600
They're not incentivized to
provide physical security

00:11:40.600 --> 00:11:42.040
for the data centers.

00:11:42.040 --> 00:11:44.110
They're not incentivized
to make decisions

00:11:44.110 --> 00:11:45.850
in the interest of the network.

00:11:45.850 --> 00:11:47.650
So they have a
very pure incentive

00:11:47.650 --> 00:11:49.460
to just hash as
much as possible,

00:11:49.460 --> 00:11:52.310
get paid, rinse and repeat.

00:11:52.310 --> 00:11:54.440
In the case of Ripple,
since the validators

00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:57.350
are chosen by the users, if
a validator, for example,

00:11:57.350 --> 00:11:59.930
votes against a block
size increase or something

00:11:59.930 --> 00:12:03.260
like that if there were
an issue in Ripple, then

00:12:03.260 --> 00:12:06.462
you would eventually find
that users would no longer add

00:12:06.462 --> 00:12:07.670
that validator to their list.

00:12:07.670 --> 00:12:10.250
And so that validator would
slowly lose influence.

00:12:10.250 --> 00:12:13.220
And so it's not as
much of a system that's

00:12:13.220 --> 00:12:15.080
tailored to users
like Bitcoin is,

00:12:15.080 --> 00:12:17.720
where anyone can just
run a node and it just

00:12:17.720 --> 00:12:20.360
auto-configures itself,
connects to the network.

00:12:20.360 --> 00:12:22.580
You do have to do that
validator selection manually.

00:12:22.580 --> 00:12:23.900
You have to think about--

00:12:23.900 --> 00:12:26.360
politically speaking--
which validators

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:28.920
do you want to empower
with your node, et cetera?

00:12:28.920 --> 00:12:31.520
So it is more
targeted at actively

00:12:31.520 --> 00:12:34.262
being managed by companies,
things of that nature.

00:12:34.262 --> 00:12:36.470
But I think the reason that
that makes a lot of sense

00:12:36.470 --> 00:12:38.210
is because when you
actually go out there

00:12:38.210 --> 00:12:41.130
into the market,
the evil people--

00:12:41.130 --> 00:12:42.600
you mentioned I'm an anarchist.

00:12:42.600 --> 00:12:46.200
So I really want to
empower people, right?

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:49.600
But the people that you've got
to fight are not all the banks.

00:12:49.600 --> 00:12:53.330
There are a few very,
very powerful players

00:12:53.330 --> 00:12:55.729
in the market that take
a little bit off the top,

00:12:55.729 --> 00:12:57.770
and those are the people
that you want to bypass.

00:12:57.770 --> 00:12:58.770
And then everyone else--

00:12:58.770 --> 00:13:00.812
there's a lot of small
banks and regional banks

00:13:00.812 --> 00:13:02.270
and so on that
we've talked to that

00:13:02.270 --> 00:13:05.230
are really trying to provide
better user experience.

00:13:05.230 --> 00:13:07.800
They're really trying to
provide lower fees, et cetera.

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:09.950
Those are the companies that we
want to work with and empower,

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:10.949
and it's not just banks.

00:13:10.949 --> 00:13:14.430
It's payment providers, mobile
money providers, and so on.

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:17.324
So that's where that
different approach comes from.

00:13:17.324 --> 00:13:18.740
And on the
centralization point, I

00:13:18.740 --> 00:13:21.031
would say that there are a
lot of different definitions

00:13:21.031 --> 00:13:23.340
of centralization,
and we're going down

00:13:23.340 --> 00:13:26.750
the list of meeting more and
more of them as we progress.

00:13:26.750 --> 00:13:29.330
One of the ones that
we don't meet yet

00:13:29.330 --> 00:13:33.440
is that we still run a majority
of the trusted validators.

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:35.090
But that's something
that we're--

00:13:35.090 --> 00:13:38.530
this year-- going to start
rolling out in terms of,

00:13:38.530 --> 00:13:41.270
we have already got a lot of
third-party validators running.

00:13:41.270 --> 00:13:44.010
So people are going to start
trusting them this year.

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:47.340
And so that's just one more
step to go in that direction.

00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:50.720
And I think if I compare it to
where we were with Bitcoin--

00:13:50.720 --> 00:13:53.300
with Bitcoin, we had some
level of decentralization.

00:13:53.300 --> 00:13:55.704
Again, meeting some of the
definitions but not all.

00:13:55.704 --> 00:13:57.620
For instance, there's
no geographic diversity.

00:13:57.620 --> 00:14:00.497
It's very concentrated
in China right now.

00:14:00.497 --> 00:14:02.830
But we didn't have a very
good roadmap in order to-- how

00:14:02.830 --> 00:14:06.530
to overcome that, because
the system is really--

00:14:06.530 --> 00:14:11.180
it's just centers are set up
in a, I would now say, bad way.

00:14:11.180 --> 00:14:13.920
Whereas with Ripple, the
incentives are in order.

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:16.490
And so it's just a matter
of validators having

00:14:16.490 --> 00:14:19.070
the right amount of
operational histories

00:14:19.070 --> 00:14:20.750
so people actually
start trusting them,

00:14:20.750 --> 00:14:22.708
and us having enough
confidence in the software

00:14:22.708 --> 00:14:25.831
to actually continuously let go
of more and more of the reigns

00:14:25.831 --> 00:14:26.330
here.

00:14:26.330 --> 00:14:30.440
So I think, for Ripple,
it's a clearer roadmap

00:14:30.440 --> 00:14:33.080
to get to a very high
level of decentralization.

00:14:33.080 --> 00:14:36.440
CHRIS LARSEN: And bottom
