STEFAN THOMAS: So what this is
trying to illustrate is if you

00:18:07.210 --> 00:18:08.800
deploy Interledger
on some network--

00:18:08.800 --> 00:18:12.760
and we envision that there will
probably be a global instance

00:18:12.760 --> 00:18:16.150
of it, just like the internet
has a global instance--

00:18:16.150 --> 00:18:18.490
then you have these
different nodes--

00:18:18.490 --> 00:18:20.290
these little blue nodes here.

00:18:20.290 --> 00:18:23.230
And we call them connectors,
but they're basically

00:18:23.230 --> 00:18:24.510
like routers and IPs.

00:18:24.510 --> 00:18:27.169
So they basically take
in packets on one side.

00:18:27.169 --> 00:18:28.960
They look at the
destination on the packet.

00:18:28.960 --> 00:18:30.910
They compare it to
their routing table,

00:18:30.910 --> 00:18:32.590
and then they
forward that packet

00:18:32.590 --> 00:18:34.150
towards that destination.

00:18:34.150 --> 00:18:37.060
Whenever you look at any kind
of blockchain presentation,

00:18:37.060 --> 00:18:39.010
there's a pretty
good chance you'll

00:18:39.010 --> 00:18:42.700
see some kind of graphic
that has nodes connected

00:18:42.700 --> 00:18:46.030
by lines, some kind of graph.

00:18:46.030 --> 00:18:50.660
And you'll hear things like,
Bitcoin is the TCP/IP of money.

00:18:50.660 --> 00:18:54.340
And when we hear that, we cringe
a little bit, because if you

00:18:54.340 --> 00:18:58.060
know anything about how TCP/IP
works and how Bitcoin works,

00:18:58.060 --> 00:19:00.010
they are very
different protocols.

00:19:00.010 --> 00:19:03.142
They're two very different
things in a very different way.

00:19:03.142 --> 00:19:04.600
And so the challenge
that we always

00:19:04.600 --> 00:19:06.520
have when we talk
about Interledger is it

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:08.830
is actually a lot like TCP/IP.

00:19:08.830 --> 00:19:10.690
And through this
little presentation,

00:19:10.690 --> 00:19:14.050
I want to try to convince
you as to why I say that.

00:19:14.050 --> 00:19:17.576
But people already have
usually seen some kind

00:19:17.576 --> 00:19:18.700
of blockchain presentation.

00:19:18.700 --> 00:19:20.860
It already looks
a lot like this,

00:19:20.860 --> 00:19:23.530
but is a little bit
more superficial

00:19:23.530 --> 00:19:25.840
in terms of the similarities.

00:19:25.840 --> 00:19:28.540
And so if I want to send a
packet into this network,

00:19:28.540 --> 00:19:31.870
I just send it to whichever
connect I'm connected to,

00:19:31.870 --> 00:19:34.960
and it should find its
way to whatever receiver

00:19:34.960 --> 00:19:36.350
I've put on it.

00:19:36.350 --> 00:19:38.970
So in that way, it's
a lot like TCP/IP.

00:19:38.970 --> 00:19:41.620
Now, you might say, OK, so
you're routing these packets,

00:19:41.620 --> 00:19:44.830
but how does actual
money really move?

00:19:44.830 --> 00:19:48.550
So the way that that works
is that once you have a path

00:19:48.550 --> 00:19:50.410
and you're sending
these packets,

00:19:50.410 --> 00:19:53.470
each link is responsible
for its own settlement.

00:19:53.470 --> 00:19:57.370
So what we tend to do is if
you have two connectors that

00:19:57.370 --> 00:20:01.030
have a peering relationship
with each other,

00:20:01.030 --> 00:20:02.860
they're going to
have this packet

00:20:02.860 --> 00:20:04.334
traffic going back and forth.

00:20:04.334 --> 00:20:06.250
And so they're going to
look at those packets,

00:20:06.250 --> 00:20:08.590
and then they're going
to eventually settle.

00:20:08.590 --> 00:20:10.439
And for the core
of the network, it

00:20:10.439 --> 00:20:12.730
makes the most sense to settle
through a digital asset.

00:20:12.730 --> 00:20:14.440
And the reason for
that is that they

00:20:14.440 --> 00:20:18.350
are very easy to move
internationally across borders.

00:20:18.350 --> 00:20:21.580
You have very low costs in
terms of when you move them.

00:20:21.580 --> 00:20:23.080
And since you're
going to have a lot

00:20:23.080 --> 00:20:24.840
of inbound and
outbound traffic, it

00:20:24.840 --> 00:20:27.010
makes sense to just stay
in that digital asset

00:20:27.010 --> 00:20:29.260
to do all of your settlements.

00:20:29.260 --> 00:20:32.050
But of course, the
majority of people-- users

00:20:32.050 --> 00:20:34.810
out there-- don't actually have
easy access to digital assets

00:20:34.810 --> 00:20:35.740
yet.

00:20:35.740 --> 00:20:39.070
And so you do need
some form of support

00:20:39.070 --> 00:20:41.171
for traditional payment systems.

00:20:41.171 --> 00:20:43.420
And the interesting thing
is that all these settlement

00:20:43.420 --> 00:20:47.950
networks really do is move
payments across, or move money.

00:20:47.950 --> 00:20:50.840
And so that's something
that is supported by all

00:20:50.840 --> 00:20:52.092
the legacy payment networks.

00:20:52.092 --> 00:20:53.800
So what we can actually
do is we can just

00:20:53.800 --> 00:20:55.690
aggregate to a greater degree.

00:20:55.690 --> 00:20:58.450
So we wait a little bit
longer before we settle,

00:20:58.450 --> 00:21:00.520
and then we send one
big payment across.

00:21:00.520 --> 00:21:02.020
So you see that
at the beginning,

00:21:02.020 --> 00:21:03.310
here with the sender--

00:21:03.310 --> 00:21:06.250
down there-- and the
receiver in the upper-right--

00:21:06.250 --> 00:21:08.950
where those settlements
are happening a little less

00:21:08.950 --> 00:21:10.810
frequently, and they're
a little bit bigger.

00:21:10.810 --> 00:21:12.380
And they're probably a
little bit more expensive,

00:21:12.380 --> 00:21:13.754
but they can settle
lots and lots

00:21:13.754 --> 00:21:15.730
of these individual packets.

00:21:15.730 --> 00:21:17.230
And so with this
architecture, what

00:21:17.230 --> 00:21:20.110
that means is that from
an end-to-end perspective,

00:21:20.110 --> 00:21:23.350
we can send a packet at
incredibly low latency.

00:21:23.350 --> 00:21:27.220
We can send it at an incredibly
low incremental cost.

00:21:27.220 --> 00:21:28.720
And so that's
really what makes it

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:29.950
feel a lot like the internet.

00:21:29.950 --> 00:21:32.860
You can really just connect
to lots of different services

00:21:32.860 --> 00:21:34.360
and pay for lots
of different things

00:21:34.360 --> 00:21:37.022
without accumulating a lot
of fees while doing that.

00:21:37.022 --> 00:21:38.980
And then, sure there's
a settlement eventually,

00:21:38.980 --> 00:21:42.130
and hopefully these
last mile settlements

00:21:42.130 --> 00:21:45.220
will get more efficient-- just
like internet connectivity went

00:21:45.220 --> 00:21:49.270
from 56K modems all the
way up to what we have now

00:21:49.270 --> 00:21:50.860
where I have Google Fiber.

00:21:50.860 --> 00:21:52.060
So I'm very happy with that.

00:21:56.550 --> 00:22:00.370
So yeah, here's a little chart
of the actual architecture.

00:22:00.370 --> 00:22:03.244
And again, if you're
familiar with TCP/IP,

00:22:03.244 --> 00:22:04.660
they draw the same
kind of picture

00:22:04.660 --> 00:22:07.917
with the four layers,
which is sometimes called

00:22:07.917 --> 00:22:09.000
the internet architecture.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:11.799
It's a little bit less detailed
than the OSI architecture,

00:22:11.799 --> 00:22:13.090
but I won't bore you with that.

00:22:13.090 --> 00:22:16.360
It's just a reference for
the people that know that.

00:22:16.360 --> 00:22:20.410
So the four layers actually
work very similarly

00:22:20.410 --> 00:22:22.360
to the four layers in TCP/IP.

00:22:22.360 --> 00:22:24.640
So I just want to go
through those four

00:22:24.640 --> 00:22:27.650
to give you a sense of how
this all works together.

00:22:27.650 --> 00:22:29.890
The way you should think
about the Interledger layer

00:22:29.890 --> 00:22:32.050
is-- that's essentially
an abstraction layer.

00:22:32.050 --> 00:22:34.030
So that's basically
the thing that you

00:22:34.030 --> 00:22:36.670
have all the different ways
of moving money below it,

00:22:36.670 --> 00:22:38.295
and then you have
all the different use

00:22:38.295 --> 00:22:40.570
cases for moving money
above it, and it brings them

00:22:40.570 --> 00:22:41.420
all together.

00:22:41.420 --> 00:22:43.720
So in the case of the
internet, it would be--

00:22:43.720 --> 00:22:46.840
the internet layer has
all the different ways

00:22:46.840 --> 00:22:49.180
of moving information below
it and all the different use

00:22:49.180 --> 00:22:51.031
cases building on top
of it, and so now you

00:22:51.031 --> 00:22:52.780
can have all these
different combinations.

00:22:52.780 --> 00:22:54.500
I can make a Skype
call over my WiFi.

00:22:54.500 --> 00:22:57.800
I can send an email over
my satellite internet.

00:22:57.800 --> 00:23:00.490
So it really doesn't matter
what use case I'm using

00:23:00.490 --> 00:23:01.719
and which network I'm on.

00:23:01.719 --> 00:23:03.260
I can combine them
in different ways.

00:23:03.260 --> 00:23:07.160
And so this is doing the
same thing for money.

00:23:07.160 --> 00:23:09.430
OK, now an application layer--

00:23:09.430 --> 00:23:12.300
this would be the
equivalent of HTTP, SMTP.

00:23:12.300 --> 00:23:13.630
This is use case-specific.

00:23:13.630 --> 00:23:15.820
You would make different
application layer protocols

00:23:15.820 --> 00:23:17.780
for different use cases.

00:23:17.780 --> 00:23:19.900
So one that we've
designed so far

00:23:19.900 --> 00:23:24.040
is called SPSP, or Simple
Payment Setup Protocol.

00:23:24.040 --> 00:23:27.250
And basically, all that does
is it defines what a internet

00:23:27.250 --> 00:23:28.240
identifier looks like.

00:23:28.240 --> 00:23:30.850
So think of that like
an email address.

00:23:30.850 --> 00:23:33.520
And you could send to
that type of identifier

00:23:33.520 --> 00:23:36.280
if you wanted to pay somebody
as on a peer-to-peer basis,

00:23:36.280 --> 00:23:38.260
or you could build
that into simple apps.

00:23:38.260 --> 00:23:41.050
It's not super efficient,
so it's like HTTP--

00:23:41.050 --> 00:23:44.650
general purpose
application layer protocol.

00:23:44.650 --> 00:23:46.480
You could make a much
more specialized one.

00:23:46.480 --> 00:23:48.670
So for instance, we
did an experiment

00:23:48.670 --> 00:23:51.730
where we built payments
into WebTorrent.

00:23:51.730 --> 00:23:55.600
So basically, to pay the
uploaders, but also the content

00:23:55.600 --> 00:23:58.522
creators, which I is a
really cool aspect of this.

00:23:58.522 --> 00:23:59.980
It's sufficient
enough that you can

00:23:59.980 --> 00:24:03.430
pay a lot of different parties
in the flow of whatever app

00:24:03.430 --> 00:24:04.990
or interaction that
you're a part of,

00:24:04.990 --> 00:24:07.360
and we'll see a demo
of that in a bit.

00:24:07.360 --> 00:24:09.840
But I think this is where
I expect a lot of variety,

00:24:09.840 --> 00:24:12.500
is on the application layer.

00:24:12.500 --> 00:24:14.250
Now we'll talk about
that transport layer.

00:24:14.250 --> 00:24:15.880
So if you're
familiar with TCP/IP,

00:24:15.880 --> 00:24:17.500
this is where you find your TCP.

00:24:17.500 --> 00:24:20.620
And TCP is really common to a
lot of different application

00:24:20.620 --> 00:24:22.690
layer protocols
that build on it,

00:24:22.690 --> 00:24:24.960
and it gives you some
basic services, right?

00:24:24.960 --> 00:24:28.330
It gives you sequencing of
packets so that your data comes

00:24:28.330 --> 00:24:29.800
out the right order.

00:24:29.800 --> 00:24:30.970
It gives you retransmission.

00:24:30.970 --> 00:24:34.070
If a packet gets lost, it'll
send it again, and so on.

00:24:34.070 --> 00:24:37.539
And we have a transport
layer protocol called PSK2,

00:24:37.539 --> 00:24:39.080
and it does a lot
of the same things.

00:24:39.080 --> 00:24:40.732
It's responsible
for doing things

00:24:40.732 --> 00:24:42.190
like-- if you send
a large payment,

00:24:42.190 --> 00:24:43.720
it'll split it
into smaller chunks

00:24:43.720 --> 00:24:45.010
and then reassemble them.

00:24:45.010 --> 00:24:46.900
It'll do things
like retransmission

00:24:46.900 --> 00:24:48.980
of payment packets, et cetera.

00:24:48.980 --> 00:24:51.940
So again, I'm trying
to really get across--

00:24:51.940 --> 00:24:53.740
we're copping from
the internet a lot.

00:24:53.740 --> 00:24:56.049
And we have to give
them a lot of credit,

00:24:56.049 --> 00:24:58.090
because a lot of the things
that they do actually

00:24:58.090 --> 00:25:00.730
apply to money very well.

00:25:00.730 --> 00:25:03.580
Now, the Interledger layer
is an interesting one,

00:25:03.580 --> 00:25:05.619
because that's where
all the routing happens.

00:25:05.619 --> 00:25:06.910
And when we first started out--

00:25:06.910 --> 00:25:09.250
I'll tell you one
anecdote about the design

00:25:09.250 --> 00:25:10.679
of this layer, which is--

00:25:10.679 --> 00:25:12.220
when we first started
out, we assumed

00:25:12.220 --> 00:25:13.330
that the routing
would have to be

00:25:13.330 --> 00:25:15.871
quite different, because we're
talking about money after all.

00:25:15.871 --> 00:25:18.040
We're not talking
about information.

00:25:18.040 --> 00:25:22.330
And so we knew about BGP
and how it works and so on,

00:25:22.330 --> 00:25:24.830
but we thought a lot of those
things wouldn't be applicable.

00:25:24.830 --> 00:25:27.447
We wanted to route by
the lowest cost path.

00:25:27.447 --> 00:25:29.530
We thought that that was
the most important thing,

00:25:29.530 --> 00:25:31.630
was to minimize the fees.

00:25:31.630 --> 00:25:33.220
But as we actually
building it, we

00:25:33.220 --> 00:25:37.330
realized that if you optimize
by fees, what can happen

00:25:37.330 --> 00:25:40.270
is somebody in the network
just advertises a absurd rate.

00:25:40.270 --> 00:25:43.840
So they just advertise, hey, I
can exchange $1 for 600 euros.

00:25:43.840 --> 00:25:45.280
Now, that's suddenly
the best path

00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:47.940
to take for absolutely every
payment in the entire network.

00:25:47.940 --> 00:25:49.070
Now, what do you think
is going to happen?

00:25:49.070 --> 00:25:50.710
So that node's going to go down.

00:25:50.710 --> 00:25:53.200
Obviously, that rate was
never real to begin with.

00:25:53.200 --> 00:25:56.060
And so the whole thing
just breaks down.

00:25:56.060 --> 00:25:59.350
And so one of the reasons for
the way that BGP is designed

00:25:59.350 --> 00:26:01.450
is to make the
length of the path

00:26:01.450 --> 00:26:02.980
one of the primary metrics.

00:26:02.980 --> 00:26:05.290
And what that does is
if someone advertises

00:26:05.290 --> 00:26:07.734
some ridiculous metrics,
you're still only going

00:26:07.734 --> 00:26:09.400
to take down his
immediate neighborhood,

00:26:09.400 --> 00:26:10.720
because for everyone
else, it's still going

00:26:10.720 --> 00:26:12.180
to look like a big detour--

00:26:12.180 --> 00:26:14.770
a very long path that
they don't want to take.

00:26:14.770 --> 00:26:17.890
And so it turns out
that even for money,

00:26:17.890 --> 00:26:20.260
the length of the path is
just a very good proxy for all

00:26:20.260 --> 00:26:21.670
the other things you
might be interested in,

00:26:21.670 --> 00:26:22.750
like how reliable is it?

00:26:22.750 --> 00:26:23.620
What's the latency?

00:26:23.620 --> 00:26:24.770
What's the fees?

00:26:24.770 --> 00:26:27.790
Those are all lower, or tend
to be lower, for shorter paths.

00:26:27.790 --> 00:26:29.380
And so we can do
exactly what BGP

00:26:29.380 --> 00:26:31.660
does in terms of
routing by shortest path

00:26:31.660 --> 00:26:35.130
first, and then using
other metrics to tiebreak

00:26:35.130 --> 00:26:38.560
if paths are the same
length, picking the best one.

00:26:38.560 --> 00:26:40.680
And we just basically add
fees and other metric,

00:26:40.680 --> 00:26:43.035
just like the
internet has latency.

00:26:43.035 --> 00:26:45.160
I already talked a little
bit about the settlement.

00:26:45.160 --> 00:26:46.990
The key thing to
mention here is that all

00:26:46.990 --> 00:26:48.365
we need from the
settlement layer

00:26:48.365 --> 00:26:49.670
is that it can transmit money.

00:26:49.670 --> 00:26:51.070
It doesn't have to be very fast.

00:26:51.070 --> 00:26:52.760
It doesn't have
to be very cheap.

00:26:52.760 --> 00:26:54.905
If it's slower, we
just settle less often.

00:26:54.905 --> 00:26:57.280
And just to give you some
examples of the kinds of things

00:26:57.280 --> 00:26:59.650
we've integrated
with already, there's

00:26:59.650 --> 00:27:01.510
XRP [INAUDIBLE]
plug-in, so that's

00:27:01.510 --> 00:27:03.340
settling using the XRP Ledger.

00:27:03.340 --> 00:27:05.479
That's the most efficient
plug-in right now.

00:27:05.479 --> 00:27:07.270
That's one of the
reasons that we feel good

00:27:07.270 --> 00:27:08.620
about this strategy.

00:27:08.620 --> 00:27:10.090
We're actually
seeing, in practice,

00:27:10.090 --> 00:27:12.130
that our own
products score really

00:27:12.130 --> 00:27:15.280
well on these different
metrics in terms of,

00:27:15.280 --> 00:27:17.710
what ledger would you actually
choose for settlement?

00:27:17.710 --> 00:27:19.270
We've done a
Lightning integration.

00:27:19.270 --> 00:27:20.978
So we did a little
test where we actually

00:27:20.978 --> 00:27:23.740
connected the Bitcoin Lightning
Network and the Litecoin

00:27:23.740 --> 00:27:24.960
Lightning Network together.

00:27:24.960 --> 00:27:26.020
If you're not familiar
with Lightning,

00:27:26.020 --> 00:27:28.270
it's basically a
scalability overlay network

00:27:28.270 --> 00:27:31.780
for currencies like Bitcoin.

00:27:31.780 --> 00:27:33.489
And then you could do
something like ACH.

00:27:33.489 --> 00:27:35.154
You can even do cash
if you want, right?

00:27:35.154 --> 00:27:37.690
So you can have a relationship
with an Interledger service

00:27:37.690 --> 00:27:40.180
provider where it
basically says, I give you

00:27:40.180 --> 00:27:42.850
cash ahead of time, or you
give me cash ahead of time,

00:27:42.850 --> 00:27:45.580
and then we can exchange
packets up to that amount

00:27:45.580 --> 00:27:47.140
until we reach that
balance, and then

00:27:47.140 --> 00:27:49.480
we have to settle up again.

00:27:49.480 --> 00:27:52.750
OK, now with all
