00:49:37.516 --> 00:49:40.370
So Bitcoin uses a
consensus process

00:49:40.370 --> 00:49:42.530
which is essentially based
around the assumption

00:49:42.530 --> 00:49:44.990
that a majority of
hashing power will never

00:49:44.990 --> 00:49:48.770
be held by a coordinated
malicious attacker.

00:49:48.770 --> 00:49:51.890
And so if you're watching what
the majority of hashing power

00:49:51.890 --> 00:49:56.090
is doing, you'll tend to be
on a state of the network that

00:49:56.090 --> 00:49:59.240
is reasonable and doesn't
contain reverted transactions

00:49:59.240 --> 00:50:00.330
and so on.

00:50:00.330 --> 00:50:03.880
However, the protocol as such
does allow rollbacks, right?

00:50:03.880 --> 00:50:05.810
So you can-- if somebody
else presents you

00:50:05.810 --> 00:50:08.060
with a chain that's longer,
it has more hashing power

00:50:08.060 --> 00:50:10.040
behind it-- you will
rollback your transactions

00:50:10.040 --> 00:50:11.180
and switch to that.

00:50:11.180 --> 00:50:13.610
And I know that, because I
was one of the first people

00:50:13.610 --> 00:50:18.040
to implement a full node Bitcoin
reimplementation from scratch.

00:50:18.040 --> 00:50:20.540
So I wrote that code, and it's
a very complex, annoying code

00:50:20.540 --> 00:50:21.040
to write.

00:50:21.040 --> 00:50:23.390
So I will remember that forever.

00:50:23.390 --> 00:50:25.530
On the Ripple side, such
code does not exist.

00:50:25.530 --> 00:50:27.477
There's no way to
roll back the network.

00:50:27.477 --> 00:50:28.560
Now, how is that possible?

00:50:28.560 --> 00:50:31.310
Well, the way that
Ripple works is--

00:50:31.310 --> 00:50:34.610
as I mentioned before, the
users select these validators,

00:50:34.610 --> 00:50:36.680
and then we essentially
use that input

00:50:36.680 --> 00:50:40.550
as an input to an
algorithm where

00:50:40.550 --> 00:50:43.220
we look at the graph of what
people selected and then we

00:50:43.220 --> 00:50:47.690
run a consensus on validators
that are central to that graph,

00:50:47.690 --> 00:50:50.780
or that are highly
trusted in that graph.

00:50:50.780 --> 00:50:52.710
And so it's this
two-step process.

00:50:52.710 --> 00:50:55.580
And what that means is that
when the first step is complete

00:50:55.580 --> 00:50:59.060
and you've identified which
validators you're looking for,

00:50:59.060 --> 00:51:02.600
you don't have to worry
about there being more

00:51:02.600 --> 00:51:04.490
hashing power just
over the horizon.

00:51:04.490 --> 00:51:06.230
Once you hear from
the validators that

00:51:06.230 --> 00:51:10.430
you've identified as being
the ones that are validating--

00:51:10.430 --> 00:51:12.320
or the ones that
you're listening to--

00:51:12.320 --> 00:51:14.690
then you don't have to worry
about some other validator

00:51:14.690 --> 00:51:17.000
coming in later saying, no,
actually, we decided this.

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:18.500
You just didn't
hear about it yet.

00:51:18.500 --> 00:51:22.419
And so there's no need to roll
back or to rewrite history.

00:51:22.419 --> 00:51:24.460
Once the validators have
committed to a decision,

00:51:24.460 --> 00:51:26.850
they can't change their
minds, essentially.

00:51:26.850 --> 00:51:30.510
And so that has a
couple of impacts--

00:51:30.510 --> 00:51:32.030
a couple of ways
that the protocol's

00:51:32.030 --> 00:51:32.690
different because of that.

00:51:32.690 --> 00:51:35.075
Number one, you only have to
wait for one confirmation.

00:51:35.075 --> 00:51:36.950
You wouldn't wait for
multiple confirmations,

00:51:36.950 --> 00:51:39.050
because validators
can't change their mind.

00:51:39.050 --> 00:51:42.830
You can't roll back, so there's
no probabilistic aspect to it.

00:51:42.830 --> 00:51:48.140
Number two is we can
create blocks on a cadence.

00:51:48.140 --> 00:51:51.710
So we can create blocks on
a fixed interval as opposed

00:51:51.710 --> 00:51:53.780
to a random interval
like Bitcoin,

00:51:53.780 --> 00:51:56.350
where blocks can come
out very close together.

00:51:56.350 --> 00:51:58.460
There could be no
block for a long time.

00:51:58.460 --> 00:51:59.960
Because we know
which validators are

00:51:59.960 --> 00:52:01.310
supposed to generate blocks.

00:52:01.310 --> 00:52:03.650
They can generate
them on that cadence.

